
Orders & Inventory Microservice
Python Version 3.13.5

This project is a simple yet complete microservice for managing products and orders for a tiny online store. It is built with Python and FastAPI, uses SQLAlchemy for database interaction, and is designed for easy deployment on platforms like Render.com.

The service handles basic CRUD operations for products, manages order creation with automatic stock deduction, and includes a webhook endpoint for processing payments.

Features
Product Management: Full CRUD (Create, Read, Update, Delete) operations for products.
Order Management: Create orders for products, which automatically reduces the available stock.
Transactional Integrity: Stock is only reduced if an order is successfully created.
Payment Webhook: An endpoint (/webhooks/payment) to simulate receiving a notification from a payment provider, marking an order as "paid".
Automatic API Documentation: Interactive API documentation (Swagger UI and ReDoc) is automatically generated by FastAPI.
Automated Testing: Unit and integration tests are set up with pytest using an isolated test database.
Load Testing: A locustfile.py is included for performance testing the deployed API.
API Documentation
Once the application is running, the interactive API documentation is available at:

Swagger UI: http://127.0.0.1:8000/docs
ReDoc: http://127.0.0.1:8000/redoc
You can use the Swagger UI to explore and test all API endpoints directly from your browser.

Getting Started
Follow these instructions to get the project set up and running on your local machine.

Prerequisites
Python 3.13.5
Git
Installation & Setup
git clone https://github.com/Naveen1402/GenAI-Public.git
cd inventory_microservice

Create and activate a Python virtual environment:
# For macOS / Linux
python3 -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate

Install the required dependencies:
pip install -r requirements.txt
Running the Application> With your virtual environment active, run the development server using Uvicorn:
uvicorn main:app --reload
The application will be running at http://127.0.0.1:8000. 

Testing
This project uses pytest for automated testing. The tests run against a separate, isolated SQLite database (test.db) to avoid interfering with your development data.
pytest

Deployment on Render.com
This application is configured for easy deployment on Render.

Push your code to a GitHub/GitLab repository. Make sure your requirements.txt file is committed.
Create a PostgreSQL Database on Render:
From your Render dashboard, click New > PostgreSQL.
Give it a name and select a plan (the free plan is sufficient).

Create a Web Service on Render:
From your dashboard, click New > Web Service.
Connect your GitHub/GitLab repository.
Configure the settings as follows:
Name: inventory-API
Runtime: Python 3
Build Command: pip install -r requirements.txt
Start Command: uvicorn main:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000
Under the Advanced section, add an Environment Variable:
Key: postgresql://inventory_db_h3aj_user:E43V8PdSzFTdEtP6rD146fxglsV1T5gW@dpg-d2lu20be5dus7396qjjg-a/inventory_db_h3aj

Click Create Web Service. Render will build and deploy your application.
Load Testing with Locust
You can test the performance of your deployed application using Locust.

Run Locust locally:
Point it to the URL of your deployed Render service.
locust -f locustfile.py --host https://inventory-api-lfes.onrender.com

Open the Locust web interface:
Navigate to http://localhost:8089 in your browser.
Start the test:
Enter the number of users you want to simulate and a spawn rate, then click "Start swarming". You can monitor the performance of your API in real-time.

Project Structure
.
├── main.py             # The main FastAPI application logic
├── test_main.py        # Automated tests using pytest
├── locustfile.py       # User behavior script for load testing
├── requirements.txt    # Python dependencies
├── store.db            # Local SQLite database for development
└── test.db             # Isolated SQLite database for testing
